 it happens i do lay awake for hours sometimes but i feel decent in the morning after i eventually fall asleep on my own some things that can help you sleep are a cool environment too warm can keep you awake take your shower several hours before you go to bed avoid bright lights close to bedtime try to have a quiet sleeping place try to relax and not worry about not being able to get to sleep not drinking coffee other caffeinated drinks or alcohol within a few hours of bed time can help too Narcolepsy Urinary incontinence Out-of-body experience Sleep apnea Caffeine Social rule Clinical depression Sleep debt Sleep disorder Lucid dreaming Daylight saving time Diazepam Anxiety Breastfeeding Mattress Bipolar disorder Shaggy dog story Episodes of Lost (Season 1) Carpal tunnel syndrome The Amber Spyglass Avenue Q Hypoglycemia Sedative Cannabis (drug) Chronic fatigue syndrome Coffee Delayed sleep phase syndrome Dream Humphrey Bogart Hypnosis Traumatic brain injury Milton H. Erickson Drowning Migraine Reflexology Sin City Dyslexia The Subtle Knife Common cold Suicide methods STS-62 First aid Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma Electroencephalography Psychosis Apollo 8 Prostate cancer The Catcher in the Rye Attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder Dimenhydrinate Opportunity rover timeline for 2004 March EastEnders Psychedelics, dissociatives and deliriants Time Oh My Goddess! Knots Landing Sauna Yoga Sutras of Patanjali The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe Obsessive-compulsive disorder Hormone replacement therapy (trans) The Shining (film) Circadian rhythm Similarities between the Bible and the Qur'an Meditation Childbirth Charles Darwin's illness Autism Satchel Paige Borderline personality disorder Friends Fibromyalgia One Tree Hill (TV series) Everwood Word of Wisdom Skinny Dip Snoring Paracetamol Stomach cancer Thermoregulation Sleeping sickness Philosophical skepticism Canonical hours Panic attack Energy drink Alcoholism Aerial (dance move) 2005 trial of Michael Jackson Tea Wild at H